<HEAD>Authorities Recover Priceless Artifacts Stolen From National Museum</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have recovered scores of priceless
jade, gold and stone artifacts taken in the <DATE>1985</DATE> Chistmas Day
robbery of the <ORGANIZATION>National Museum of Anthropology</ORGANIZATION>, the federal attorney
general's office said.
   Federal agents found 133 of the 140 stolen treasures from the
ancient Mayan, <LOCATION>Aztec</LOCATION>, Zapotec and Mixtec civilizations in canvas
sacks stashed in a home in suburban <LOCATION>Mexico City</LOCATION>, the daily <PERSON>Excelsior</PERSON>
said.
   It said 10 people were arrested.
   The story was confirmed <DATE>Sunday</DATE> by an agent at the attorney
general's office. The agent, who requested anonymity, said experts
were authenticating the artifacts prior to an official announcement.
   The artifacts were recovered <DATE>Saturday</DATE> during a series of raids on
several residences in <LOCATION>Mexico City</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Excelsior</PERSON> said. It said Deputy
Attorney General <PERSON>Javier Coello Trejo</PERSON>, head of the narcotics
enforcement division, led the raids.
   Among the items recovered were a Zapotec mask of the bat god
Murielago and an obsidian Aztec sculpture of a monkey. Experts have
described them as two of the most valuable pieces in a museum
crammed with irreplaceable objects from civilizations dating back
thousands of years.
   Excelsior said the suspects arrested <DATE>Saturday</DATE> include two
brothers identified as the masterminds of the crime that stunned the
nation and led to an international search for the treasures looted
from seven display cases early <DATE>Dec. 25, 1985</DATE>.
   Many of the artifacts came from such important archeological
sites as <LOCATION>Palenque</LOCATION> in southern <LOCATION>Mexico</LOCATION> and Chicen-Itza on the <LOCATION>Yucatan
Peninsula</LOCATION>.
   Excelsior said authorities believe the loot has been in the same
place, a house in an affluent middle-class neighborhood called
Satellite, since it was stolen. Officials have long maintained that
many of the items were too well-known to be sold on the open market
and that they were still in <LOCATION>Mexico</LOCATION>.
   Excelsior said the recovered artifacts include a famous Mayan
turquoise mosaic, a Mixtec gold and conch shell necklace and several
other pieces of jewelry. It did not say anything about the seven
items that were not recovered.
</TEXT>
