<LEADPARA>  IT'S not your usual night at the opera.;   The singers on stage are dressed in
the feathered finery and crimson robes of pre-Columbian priests. The dancers
are moving to the percussive sounds made by rattles strapped to their feet. A
minimalist computer accompaniment and the pungent aroma of incense waft over
the small invited audience.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Arts &amp; Books  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  THE RITE STUFF
OPERA SAN JOSE WORKS TO TURN SACRED TEXTS, MODERN
MUSIC INTO AN OPERA OF THE CONTINENT BEFORE
COLUMBUS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Opera  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The scene is from a workshop presentation of an excerpt from "<PERSON>Popol Vuh</PERSON>," a
commissioned opera-in-progress, which could become the most ambitious project
attempted by <ORGANIZATION>Opera San Jose.</ORGANIZATION>;   With a score by prize-winning electronic
composer <ORGANIZATION>Allen Strange</ORGANIZATION>, a libretto by <PERSON>Robert Jenkins</PERSON> and choreography by <PERSON>David
A. Vargas</PERSON>, the 16-minute excerpt staged recently at <LOCATION>San Jose State</LOCATION> was as
visually stunning and exotic as anything in "Aida" or "L'Africaine.";   This
operatic pie-slice is decidedly unorthodox, using computer-generated music
throughout and no acoustic instruments.;   <ORGANIZATION>Composer Strange</ORGANIZATION>, a nationally
recognized <ORGANIZATION>San Jose State</ORGANIZATION> faculty member, had never written an opera before.
He ran across a translation of "Popol Vuh" in a bookstore -- misplaced in the
cooking section. He and librettist <PERSON>Jenkins</PERSON> approached Opera <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION> about
writing an opera based on the work.;   "I always thought of opera as
19th-century TV," he commented after accepting a commission to start on the
project.;   A number of listeners at the <DATE>Aug. 22</DATE> presentation were so
impressed that they stayed to see a second run-through later the same evening
-- this, despite the use of the Central American texts, three languages, the
electronic score and some moments that seemed more like anthropology than
opera.;   Indeed, some accurately inflected Quiche-Mayan spoken texts had been
provided on audio tape by <ORGANIZATION>Stanford</ORGANIZATION> anthropology professor <PERSON>James Fox</PERSON>. They were
sprinkled in with the singing in English and Spanish.;   <LOCATION>Opera San Jose</LOCATION> has
taken a cautious approach to the project in this recession year. The company
gave the green light for the 16-minute workshop scene with makeup and
costumes. A grant of over <MONEY>$9,000</MONEY> from the <ORGANIZATION>San Jose Fine Arts Commission</ORGANIZATION> was
seed money for the mini-production, whose costs were estimated at <MONEY>$14,000</MONEY> in
cash and <MONEY>$30,000</MONEY> in in-kind services.;   <LOCATION>Opera San Jose</LOCATION> videotaped the
workshop in order to interest potential contributors. The company has set an
<DATE>August 1992</DATE> deadline for raising the "<MONEY>$80,000</MONEY> to <MONEY>$100,000</MONEY>" needed for
completion of the libretto and score, according to executive director <PERSON>Craig
Palmer</PERSON>. Says <PERSON>Palmer</PERSON>, "This piece is at least three to four years away" from
the main stage.;   The basis of the libretto is the opening portion of "<PERSON>Popol
Vuh</PERSON>," the sacred book of the ancient Quiche Mayas, whose descendants still
survive in the highlands of Guatemala.;   The earliest written versions of
"Popol Vuh" were set down on scrolls in the mid-16th century by native priests
who feared that otherwise their indigenous tradition would be wiped out by the
Spanish conquistadors.;   The opera adaptation of "Popol Vuh" represents an
unusual attempt at an honest and historically informed portrayal of a tale
drawn from an indigenous American culture.;   Older operas were not nearly as
true to their historic sources. The two "Montezuma" operas by <PERSON>Karl Heinrich
Graun</PERSON> (1755) and <PERSON>Roger Sessions</PERSON> (<DATE>1962</DATE>) are rooted firmly in the European
operatic tradition. And two better-known works -- <PERSON>Purcell</PERSON>'s "The Indian Queen"
(1694) and <PERSON>Offenbach</PERSON>'s "La Perichole" (1868) -- are merely excuses for
European singers with thoroughly European scores to don exotic finery and play
out painfully implausible tales. Unlike "<PERSON>Popol Vuh</PERSON>," none of these is written
from the perspective of New World peoples.;   But despite the admirable
intentions, producer <PERSON>Daniel Helfgot</PERSON> had to overcome resistance when he sought
out dancers who could perform in the Aztec and Mayan traditions from the local
group Tezkatlipoka. "The dancers were suspicious," said <PERSON>Helfgot</PERSON>, an urbane
emigre from <PERSON>Buenos Aires</PERSON> and the only Latin American involved on the creative
team. "They wondered, 'What do these Caucasians want to do?' Now they have
joined us. But we are sensitive to them.";   Asked about the possibility of
offending the surviving descendants of the Quiche Mayas, librettist <PERSON>Jenkins</PERSON>
said, "I've worried a lot over it. . . . (Therefore) we're staying as close as
possible to the sacred text.";   Apart from this problem, there's also a
question of how well the stories will translate to the operatic stage. To this
critic, the excerpt at <ORGANIZATION>San Jose State</ORGANIZATION> offered more color than drama. The
decision to stick closely to the Mayan codex appears to be pushing the work
toward ceremony and away from plot development and a strong set of central
characters. Most of the scene played like something akin to Pharaonic rites or
a religious service.;   Baroque composers faced a similar quandary in dealing
with sacred texts. The prolific opera composer <PERSON>Handel</PERSON> put his Biblical works
into oratorio (concert) form rather than opera. Bach created his Passions for
use in the church rather than on the stage; modern-day operatic stagings of
his great "St. <PERSON>Matthew</PERSON>'s Passion" have not met with favor, despite repeated
attempts.;   Still, it's clear that <LOCATION>Opera San Jose</LOCATION> has made great strides,
demonstrating its excellent production skills even in the bare-bones <ORGANIZATION>San Jose
State Studio Theater</ORGANIZATION>. The ensemble had done its homework, and the presentation
had integrity.;   As for theatricality, the overrunning of the Mayan religious
rites by the conquistadors in one portion provided a vivid if melodramatic
touch.;   While the fund-raising effort goes on, the <LOCATION>Opera San Jose</LOCATION> creative
team, from artistic director <PERSON>Irene Dalis</PERSON> to conductor <PERSON>Barbara Day Turner</PERSON> to
choreographer <PERSON>David A. Vargas</PERSON>, are hoping enough backers will be found to make
the opera happen.;   <ORGANIZATION>Composer Strange</ORGANIZATION>, meanwhile, has musical sketches galore,
with five discs of computer-synthesized flute music alone.;   "With
computer-generated music, every minute (performed) takes about 18 hours of
work" by the composer, Strange says. "And that isn't much different than
traditional composing (for voice and orchestra).";   If this project catches
on, and the entire five-volume set of sacred writings of the Quiche Mayas were
to be turned into opera, Strange's score would make <PERSON>Richard Wagner</PERSON>'s epic
"Ring" cycle look like a minuet. If dramatized at the current rate, the entire
set would entail well in excess of 60 hours of music.;   Now that would be an
opera to remember. (box)  </TEXT>
