<HL> How Grave Looter At a Mexican Site Drools Over Relics --- Archaeologists Chase Him From Old Olmec Ruins; The Big Illicit Art Trade </HL>
<AUTHOR> Jonathan Kandell (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> LATAM </CO>
<DATELINE> COPALILLO, Mexico  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In this isolated valley where peasants furrow their cornfields with mule-drawn wooden plows, archaeologists are unearthing a cradle of ancient Mexican civilization -- an Olmec settlement that flourished between <DATE>1200</DATE> and 600 B.C. 

   <PERSON>Pablo Morales</PERSON> got here before them. 
For two years, he and several confederates looted the site, making off with a trove of figurines that they sold to private collectors. 
But the grave robber was chased from the site in <DATE>1983</DATE>, when the Mexican government got wind of the momentous find and took charge of the zone. 

   Now, <PERSON>Mr. Morales</PERSON> is on a furtive return visit. 
As he stands atop a large burial mound that is still sealed, his larcenous instincts are stirring. 
"The Olmec chieftains were buried with their most valuable possessions," says <PERSON>Mr. Morales</PERSON>, arms across his chest, mimicking a corpse clutching its earthly goods. 
"Just think of it -- idols, pottery, jewelry, a treasure under our feet." 

   <PERSON>Mr. Morales</PERSON> is back by invitation of this reporter. 
We have cut a deal: I have government permission to visit Copalillo, about 150 miles south of <LOCATION>Mexico City</LOCATION>. 
He has agreed to be my guide and enlighten me about the illicit -- and thriving -- trade in art treasures. 

   But Copalillo alone isn't enough of a lure for the wily grave robber. 
After some haggling, I agree to buy a piece he says he has looted from another site, a small, delicately sculpted duck, which he attributes to the Totonacas, a 13th-century tribe from <LOCATION>Veracruz</LOCATION> on the <ORGANIZATION>Gulf Coast</ORGANIZATION>. 
I plan to donate it to the <ORGANIZATION>National Museum of Anthropology</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Mexico City</LOCATION>. 
The purchase sets me back <MONEY>$150</MONEY>. 

   Deals like this one have helped swell the illicit world trade in art treasures to about <MONEY>$1 billion</MONEY> a year, according to the <ORGANIZATION>Cultural Property Advisory Committee</ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> government-administered agency. 
<LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> and Mexican laws bar the smuggling of pre-Columbian objects. 
But many other nations, among them <LOCATION>France</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>, would welcome such treasures. 

   Museum officials, archaeologists and dealers say many relics continue to be sold in the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>, only more surreptitiously. 
Unscrupulous dealers do a busy trade in their back offices and apartments. 
It is easy enough to falsify papers claiming these antiquities were held for decades by collectors in <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION>. 

   "Not long ago, we were offered a first-rate, ancient Egyptian relief," recalls <PERSON>Thomas Seligman</PERSON>, deputy director at the Fine Arts Museum of <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION>. 
"We turned it down after our research showed it had been illegally dug up. 
Even then, the dealer assured us he could arrange the proper documentation." 

   <PERSON>Mr. Morales</PERSON> has made a living in this shady business for decades. 
A short, squat man in his 60s, he began his career as a small-time dry goods merchant 40 years ago, traveling the peasant villages of central <LOCATION>Mexico</LOCATION>. 
In partial payment for his wares, he often accepted pre-Columbian relics unearthed by the peasants from their plots. 
Later, he would sell them to dealers or collectors in <LOCATION>Mexico City</LOCATION>. 

   If a piece was particularly valuable, <PERSON>Mr. Morales</PERSON> would locate the field where it was found and supervise the looting of the site. 
Within a few years, his dry-goods trade was no more than a cover-up for his more profitable dealings in antiquities. 

   But there were drawbacks. 
He was jailed twice, and he says he escaped imprisonment other times by paying the police. 
He uses false names at times, and he makes a point of never giving his clients his address or phone number in <LOCATION>Mexico City</LOCATION>. 
"I check them out, and if we trust each other, I call a few days before visiting," he says. 

   Forgeries are another danger. 
For decades, skilled artisans have reproduced pre-Columbian relics and sold them as genuine. 
<PERSON>Mr. Morales</PERSON> concedes his suppliers occasionally have passed him fraudulent pieces. 
"Some are so good, they can fool me," he says. 
"It's a terrible thing, because even if I sell them to a client in good faith, my reputation can be ruined." 

   The road to Copalillo leads past white ibises and mottled cattle strolling in the shallows of a turquoise lake. 
Asphalt eventually surrenders to gravel, and the path winds down a ravine into Copalillo, a town of mostly thatched-roof huts clinging to cracked gullies. 

   This is a world little changed since the arrival of the Spanish conquistadors more than 400 years ago. 
The peasants speak mostly Nahuatl, the Aztec language. 
There isn't an electric wire or combustion engine in sight. 
The wet season has lifted the corn stalks from the arid soil and blanketed the hills with shrubbery. 

   The Olmec zone is at the southern end of the valley near the confluence of two rivers. 
Because of the daily rains, archaeological work has been temporarily suspended, but the site remains protected by guards. 

   Besides the burial mound, archaeologists have uncovered a canal and dam wall, perhaps the earliest use of irrigation in the <LOCATION>New World</LOCATION>, and a four-foot-tall stone head of an obese, turbaned man. 
The findings confirm theories that the Olmecs, once thought to have settled only along the <ORGANIZATION>Gulf Coast</ORGANIZATION>, were well ensconced in the state of <LOCATION>Guerrero</LOCATION>, closer to the <LOCATION>Pacific</LOCATION>. 
They may even have originated here. 

   <PERSON>Mr. Morales</PERSON> is disappointed that more figurines have not been dug up. 
"Archaeologists nowadays don't care about idols," he says. 
"They get more excited about garbage piles and latrines." 

   He isn't entirely wrong. 
"Ecological archaeology" has become the vogue. 
Scholars sift through refuse heaps, irrigation canals and house remnants in hopes of reconstructing the diet, demography and social structure of the ancients. 
Their interest in the aesthetics of stone figurines and jewelry has waned. 

   The mackerel sky thickens, and <PERSON>Mr. Morales</PERSON> is anxious to drive back to <LOCATION>Mexico City</LOCATION> before the rains seal off the valley. 
By the time the car reaches the mountainous exit road, grape-size drops are splattering on the hood. 
The ground melts and the wheels skid as the vehicle inches up the incline. 
Wretched as it is, Copalillo is a welcome sight. 
We stop at a small store, where <PERSON>Mr. Morales</PERSON> used to buy relics. 

   The white-haired shopkeeper recognizes <PERSON>Mr. Morales</PERSON> and greets him in a Nahuatl-Spanish hybrid. 
He invites us home to look at some Olmec artifacts which peasants have unearthed not far from the archaeological site. 
Over a meal of stewed iguana that tastes like game-bird, we inspect the pieces: clay figurines of infants with Oriental faces, a glazed ceramic death-mask, and sinuous reptiles and jaguars carved from jadeite and onyx. 

   <PERSON>Mr. Morales</PERSON>, excited, asks me to step outside a moment. 
He says we could sell the pieces for 10 times what the shopkeeper is asking. 
But I remind him of one of the terms of our agreement. 
Other than my purchase, he'd agreed not to buy or sell any relics on this trip. 
Disgusted, he informs our host that we aren't in the market just now. 

   On the way back to <LOCATION>Mexico City</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Mr. Morales</PERSON> defends the practice of grave robbing. 
Looters have found many significant archaeological sites in the country, he says. 
Besides, he adds, <LOCATION>Mexico</LOCATION> will never exhaust its pre-Columbian treasures. 
"The whole nation is one big archaeological site," he says. 

   That isn't far from the truth. 
The <ORGANIZATION>National Institute of Anthropology and History</ORGANIZATION>, which is preparing an archaeological atlas of the country, estimates there are some 35,000 known pre-Columbian sites that have at least two or three structures other than simple dwellings. 
"The entire Mexican army could not guard that many sites," says <PERSON>Joaquin Garcia Barcena</PERSON>, director of historical monuments for the institute. 

   Even Mexican museum officials concede that looters often act as inadvertent scouts for serious archaeological work. 
The trick is not giving them enough time to devastate a site before scholars arrive. 
In the <DATE>1960s</DATE> and <DATE>1970s</DATE>, scores of Mayan monuments along the Mexico-Guatemala border were destroyed by grave robbers interested only in selling the reliefs and sculptures to dealers in <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION> and the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> 

   "To see relics like those ripped from their archaeological context is like reading a few pages and burning the rest of the book," says <PERSON>Roberto Garcia Moll</PERSON>, director of <LOCATION>Mexico City</LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>National Museum of Anthropology</ORGANIZATION>. 

   After dropping <PERSON>Mr. Morales</PERSON> off in <LOCATION>Mexico City</LOCATION>, I dutifully head for the <ORGANIZATION>National Museum of Anthropology</ORGANIZATION> to donate the relic I bought from the grave robber. 
The director, <PERSON>Mr. Garcia Moll</PERSON>, carefully inspects my duck, and returns it to me. 

   "Fine piece," he says. 
"You can keep it." 
I'm taken aback. 
"Really good craftsmanship," he adds with a smile. 
"But it's still a forgery." 

</TEXT>
