<HEADLINE>
<P>
TRAVELER'S DIARY: INTRIGUING RUINS AT COBA AND TULUM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By HORACE SUTTON, Sutton is a New York travel columnist. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
COBA, Mexico 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Today we breached the jungle at the "Queen City of the Yucatan," hub of a 
civilization that lasted for centuries. 
</P>
<P>
First explorations of the area were made in the late <DATE>1920s</DATE> and early <DATE>1930s</DATE>, but 
this once-vast city, most of whose estimated 6,500 structures remain hidden 
beneath a tangle of rain forest, did not really begin to be uncovered until 
<DATE>1972</DATE>. 
</P>
<P>
Maryknoll sisters arranged medicine and food drops until a landing strip was 
peeled away. Now, there is a road, and travelers who want a break from <LOCATION>Cancun</LOCATION>, 
roughly 100 miles away, can rumble in by bus. 
</P>
<P>
Among the other discoveries they will make at the end of a longish tramp along 
jungle trails is the <ORGANIZATION>Nohoch Mul</ORGANIZATION> pyramid, more than 120 feet tall. 
</P>
<P>
It takes 120 aching steps to reach the top. But from that lofty perch one can 
survey pyramid mounds that rise above the plain and are especially visible when 
sunrise or sunset casts shadows over the endless carpet of green. 
</P>
<P>
Just to the left of <ORGANIZATION>Nohoch Mul</ORGANIZATION> is a 400-foot square leveled terrace bearing 
evidence of houses that once stood on what the archeologists call "The Great 
Platform." 
</P>
<P>
Near the plaza in front of the pyramid is a stele, or tablet, depicting a Mayan 
ruler standing atop two kneeling slaves, with two other slaves kneeling nearby. 
</P>
<P>
The Mayan culture endures, and candlesticks, money and flowers are often placed 
at the foot of monuments. Some of the stelae, covered now by straw canopies, 
are 10 to 15 feet tall. 
</P>
<P>
Conveniently -- albeit almost incongruously -- a <ORGANIZATION>Club Med</ORGANIZATION> has risen at <ORGANIZATION>Coba</ORGANIZATION>. 
</P>
<P>
A two-story inn encircles a swimming pool and overlooks a thatched-roof 
pavilion. It offers air-conditioned rooms at <MONEY>$42</MONEY> a night double occupancy, with 
breakfast an additional <MONEY>$5</MONEY>. 
</P>
<P>
<ORGANIZATION>Coba</ORGANIZATION> lies at the hub of several dozen ancient roads, one of them stretching 
almost 60 miles. These highways, both ceremonial and utilitarian, once formed 
the largest network in <LOCATION>North America</LOCATION>. 
</P>
<P>
A new 30-mile stretch from the inland jungle leads to the walled seaside city 
of <LOCATION>Tulum</LOCATION>. 
</P>
<P>
Our guide, <ORGANIZATION>Raul</ORGANIZATION>, insisted that <LOCATION>Tulum</LOCATION> does not mean "wall" as some believe, but 
rather "evil-smelling ground," a sobriquet it earned because of its location 
above and around mangrove swamps. 
</P>
<P>
He said the city was also called <ORGANIZATION>Zama</ORGANIZATION>, meaning dawn, and that, too, makes sense 
because from <LOCATION>Tulum</LOCATION>'s clifftop perch one can see the sun rising out of the 
<LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION>. 
</P>
<P>
<LOCATION>Tulum</LOCATION>, open and visible, with no hint of jungle to impair the view of its 
ruins, belongs to a period, perhaps AD 700 to 1000, when the Mayan civilization 
was already in decline. The earliest-known stela here is said to date from AD 
564, but there is some argument on this point; some insist that the tablet was 
carved elsewhere and transported here. 
</P>
<P>
There is little argument that the city-fort was constructed three centuries 
before the Spaniards first came ashore in <DATE>1518</DATE>. The Spanish, viewing the city, 
called its most imposing structure <PERSON>El Castillo</PERSON>, the castle. 
</P>
<P>
Buses and rental cars are available daily in <LOCATION>Cancun</LOCATION> for the visit to <LOCATION>Tulum</LOCATION> with 
its myriad souvenir shacks. 
</P>
<P>
Now, with the 30-mile spur road to <ORGANIZATION>Coba</ORGANIZATION> and the promise of its little inn, 
<LOCATION>Tulum</LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Coba</ORGANIZATION> make for an unforgettable if somewhat exhausting trip. 
</P>
<P>
For more Club Med information, call toll-free (800) 258-2633. 
</P>
<P>
For more information on travel to <LOCATION>Mexico</LOCATION>, contact the <ORGANIZATION>Mexican Government 
Tourism Office</ORGANIZATION>, 10100 <LOCATION>Santa Monica Blvd.</LOCATION>, Suite 224, <LOCATION>Los Angeles</LOCATION> 90067, (213) 
203-8191. 
</P></TEXT>
