<LEADPARA>  THE amount of solar radiation that reached Antarctica last year may be the
highest since Earth developed an ozone shield 1 billion years ago.;   John
Frederick, an atmospheric physicist at the University of Chicago, reports in
the October issue of Geophysical Research Letters that on the worst days, the
ultraviolet radiation reaching Palmer Station was twice as bad as in 1989 or
1988.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Science &amp; Medicine  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  SOLAR RADIATION THROUGH OZONE AT ALL-TIME HIGH  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Science Scene  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Researchers have found no evidence of biological damage yet.; Dating the
Mayans; <ORGANIZATION>Southwest Texas State University</ORGANIZATION> archaeologists working in <LOCATION>Belize</LOCATION> have
found what they say may be the oldest known Mayan monument, pushing back the
time for the rise of Mayan civilization.;   The stone slab, or stela, includes
severely eroded carvings of Mayan glyphs and numbers indicating that they date
to 146 B.C. -- more than a century earlier than any previously discovered
monuments.; A lead bonanza; More than 70 tons of lead ingots that sank more
than 2,000 years ago aboard a Roman ship have figuratively turned to gold for
Italian physicists.;   The ingots have been isolated from the atmosphere for
so long that the radioactive form of lead in them has almost entirely decayed.
The physicists will use the lead to shield experiments that seek extremely
small levels of radioactivity.  </TEXT>
