<HL> LEISURE &amp; ARTS:
The Indiana Jane of Landscape Photography
---
By Robert Goldberg</HL>
<DD> 04/23/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<TEXT>
   One morning late last week I found myself 1,000 feet in the air, bouncing around in a rickety old single-engine plane. 
The engine droned half-heartedly, the chassis jolted up and down, and we barely skimmed the tops of the apartment buildings along the <LOCATION>Hudson River</LOCATION>. 
As the nose took an alarming dive for the third time, I clutched my seat belt and tried to remember why in the world I was there. 

   "<PERSON>Goldberg</PERSON>," the voice had rasped out of my answering machine. 
"I want you to go up in an airplane with a beautiful woman photographer. 
She flies around in one of those tiny propeller planes." 
The voice chuckled. 
"It shouldn't be too dangerous." 

   So there I was, gritting my teeth and looking a little green. 
The pilot turned around and smiled. 
"You're not going to get sick, are you?" he asked, thrusting a small blue bag into my hands. 
I smiled back wanly and concentrated on taking notes. 

   "Look over there," <PERSON>Marilyn Bridges</PERSON> yelled back, her beach-blond hair whipping in the wind. 
The horizon tipped up at us alarmingly. 
Ms. Bridges jammed her <ORGANIZATION>Pentax</ORGANIZATION> medium format camera into her face, and started snapping furiously out the open window. 

   For the past eight years, <PERSON>Marilyn Bridges</PERSON> has been hanging out of open airplane doors and windows, suspending herself over space, shooting landscapes from above. 
Like some combination of <PERSON>Ansel Adams</PERSON> and <LOCATION>Indiana</LOCATION> Jones -- artist and adventurer -- the coltishly attractive young photographer has been drawn to ancient, sacred sites: ceremonial pyramids of the Mayans in <LOCATION>Mexico</LOCATION>, stone circles of the Druids in <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>, the huge ground drawings in <LOCATION>Peru</LOCATION> known as the <LOCATION>Nazca</LOCATION> lines. 

   Her shadowed, textured aerial landscapes have won her Guggenheim and <ORGANIZATION>National Endowment</ORGANIZATION> for the Arts grants, and been collected by the <ORGANIZATION>Bibliotheque Nationale</ORGANIZATION>, the Museum of Modern Art and the <ORGANIZATION>International Center of Photography</ORGANIZATION>. 
Her show, "Markings," is currently on view at <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>'s Burden Gallery through <DATE>May 2</DATE>. (It then travels to the <LOCATION>Oklahoma</LOCATION> Art Center in <LOCATION>Oklahoma City</LOCATION> <DATE>June 4-Aug</DATE>. 13 and the <PERSON>Ruth Eckerd Hall</PERSON> in <LOCATION>Clearwater</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Fla.</LOCATION>, <DATE>Sept. 18-Oct</DATE>. 25. 
Subsequent shows are planned for <LOCATION>Arizona</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Ohio</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>.) 

   "I'm trying to show something people never get to see," <PERSON>Ms. Bridges</PERSON> says, "the world from God's-eye view. 
I'm above, but not that high above -- about 500 to 1,000 feet. 
I'm actually very intimate with the scene, hovering around on top of the trees." 

   While <PERSON>Ms. Bridges</PERSON> is, by definition, a landscape photographer, she draws a distinction between herself and her earth-bound counterparts. 
"In a plane, it's not like doing landscapes on the ground. 
You're moving so fast, you can't get absorbed, or take your time. 
You have to shoot fast. 
It's like <PERSON>Cartier-Bresson</PERSON> -- catching the 'decisive moment.'" 

   Ms. Bridges has photographed all over the world -- from <LOCATION>Greece</LOCATION> to the Yucatan -- but wherever she is, she keeps returning to ruined temples and line drawings scraped into the earth. 
She documents these ancient, ritualistic sites, these strange mixtures of art and religion, often produced as offerings to the gods and visible only from the sky. 
In one sense then, <PERSON>Ms. Bridges</PERSON>'s photos have an almost anthropological purpose. 
She sometimes calls herself a "visual archaeologist." 
Yet the photographer is equally adamant about the emotional component of her work, about "trying to make an artistic statement beyond just a historic document -- to evoke the spirit of the place." 

   Shot in black and white, her pictures are marked by a melancholy that hangs over the scene, a kind of mournful emptiness. 
"There is an isolation, a longing in my images," says <PERSON>Ms. Bridges</PERSON>. 
"It's almost sad, looking at the ancient ritual sites and not seeing ancient man there." 

   Thirty-eight-year-old <PERSON>Ms. Bridges</PERSON> has been taking pictures since the age of five, when she got a Brownie camera for <DATE>Christmas</DATE>. 
Her father was a photo enthusiast, and, she remembers, "I was always being photographed." 
In <DATE>1967</DATE>, at the age of 18, <PERSON>Ms. Bridges</PERSON> left her "sheltered" home in <LOCATION>New Jersey</LOCATION> and went off to <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION>'s <LOCATION>Haight-Ashbury</LOCATION> for the <DATE>Summer</DATE> of Love. 
In her teens and early 20s, she worked as a model. 

   "Actually," she recalls, "I kept wanting to get behind the camera, to go in the darkroom and watch the magic of the images coming up." 
Ms. Bridges first earned money with a camera as a travel photographer for airline magazines and women's journals. 
After a few years, however, she left magazine work to become an art photographer, and went back to get an <ORGANIZATION>MFA</ORGANIZATION> at R.I.T. 

   It was while photographing the <LOCATION>Nazca</LOCATION> lines in <LOCATION>Peru</LOCATION> in <DATE>1979</DATE> that Ms. Bridges first became fascinated with aerial photography. 
It still remains her favorite mode. 
"I like the adventure, that aspect of danger," she says, her blue eyes opening wide. 

   Turning to look out the open window of the plane, <PERSON>Ms. Bridges</PERSON> asks, "You hear that buzzer?" 
I did. 
"That's the stall buzzer -- it means the plane is close to stalling. 
We have to fly very slowly when I photograph." 
But surely, I said, you can restart a plane when it stalls out? 
"You can," she nodded, "But not when you're this low. 
There's no space to put the nose down and get the air speed up. 
You dive right into the ground." 
So what about that stall buzzer? 
I asked nervously. 
"That's the edge," she said with a little grin. 
"There's always that question -- are we going to make it this time? 
It makes me feel alive." 
It made me feel queasy. 

   Quickly changing the topic, I was glad to hear that <PERSON>Ms. Bridges</PERSON> had a second, more wholesome reason for preferring this kind of photography. 
"I love the outdoors, the earth," she said. 
"Actually, I'm a Capricorn, the earth sign. 
I love to mountain climb, to touch the earth. 
That's why I can relate to the philosophies of the Indians, their love for sacred landscapes." 

   An outdoors person, <PERSON>Ms. Bridges</PERSON> believes that "the big problem with us today is that we confine ourselves to small offices, we eat food out of tin cans, we watch TV in little living rooms. 
Man is separated from who he is, from the earth. 
We have such big egos; we think man was so primitive 2,000 years ago. 
But we've lost the things he had. 
He appreciated light and sun -- that was life. 
Today we sit in little rooms with fluorescent lights. 
It drives me crazy. 
How advanced are we?" 

   As her "Markings" show travels the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Ms. Bridges</PERSON> has a second exhibit, "<LOCATION>Greece</LOCATION>: Sacred Sanctuaries/Secular Views" currently at the <ORGANIZATION>International Museum of Photography</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Rochester</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>N.Y.</LOCATION>, through <DATE>June 7</DATE>, and is also working to raise funds for a photo show of North American Indian sacred sites. ("We always think of the pyramids of <LOCATION>Egypt</LOCATION> or the Yucatan -- but there's so much ancient history here in the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> that we've ignored -- that we're losing.") 
She's also trying to find ways to photograph in <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Saudi Arabia</LOCATION>. 

   As the plane coasted in, and rolled to a stop at <LOCATION>New Jersey</LOCATION>'s <LOCATION>Teterboro Airport</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Marilyn Bridges</PERSON> packed her camera away. 
Another good morning's work. 
And me, I wobbled out clutching the little blue airsickness bag. 
The bag, I'm proud to say, was unopened. 

   ---
   <PERSON>Mr. Goldberg</PERSON> is a New York-based free-lance writer. 

</TEXT>
